<br>
Normally it's self judgement.  Yes, if I led the raid I'd tell everyone that warriors can't roll on shields or that nifty ac 7 gloves etc, since no sane warrior would EVER use such items.  But let's face it, if it says &quot;need before greed&quot; and a warrior rolls on an item he clearly wont use (and then is reselling it later) ... well it's not the organizer's fault, it's the warrior's fault for being greedy.  You are pretty much saying &quot;tough luck, why'd you give it to him&quot; ... he got it cause he implied he &quot;needed&quot; it.<br>
<br>
No, I wasn't there.  I just find it ludicrous that you are saying that it's the organizer's fault, and not the one that abused the system.   Is it the same as the one that's wearing a 40 percent haste and rolls on the 36 percent haste cloak drop saying he 'needs' it ?  An organizer isn't gonna be able to police everyone to find out whether or not they -really- need it.  But it's a good bet if you are selling it the next day or week, you didn't really need it.<br>
